## Order / Transaction History

## Overview
Build an Order / Transaction History page that presents a list of past invoices and transactions, with capabilities to download invoices as PDF/CSV, view invoice details, and clearly display payment status. This page ties directly into Billing & Subscription Management (for invoices, plan entitlements, and billing metadata) and into the Subscription Management area (for plan changes and related entitlements). The UI should be data-forward, accessible, and performant, with clear affordances for exporting data, viewing details, and understanding payment status.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A dedicated historical ledger UI for invoices and transactions. It shows a paginated or virtualized list of past invoices/transactions, including metadata such as date, description, amount, currency, plan or product, status, and payment method when applicable.

Goals:
- Provide fast, predictable rendering of historical data, with robust client-side guards against null/undefined values.
- Enable users to download individual invoices as PDF or CSV, and to export the current view (CSV/PDF or both) for multiple records.
- Allow quick invoice viewing in a modal or drawer, including billing address, line items, taxes, totals, and payment status.
- Integrate with Billing & Subscription Management to surface and filter by subscription plan, entitlements, and billing metadata.
- Clearly indicate payment status (Paid, Unpaid, Past Due, Refunded, Canceled) with accessible color semantics.
- Provide date-range filtering, search, and quick-apply presets (Last 7/30/90 days).
- Ensure all data access follows the provided runtime safety rules (nullish coalescing, Array guards, useState defaults, etc.).

Connected features and API interactions:
- Billing & Subscription Management: Invoices, subscriptions, plan changes, and billing metadata are related data points. Invoice items, totals, tax, and billing address should be retrieved or joined if needed.
- Subscription Management: Plan names, entitlements, and billing metadata should be surfaced in the list where relevant (e.g., plan name per invoice).
- No external UI data visualizations are required, but the page should gracefully handle optional data (e.g., missing billing address, missing line items).

UI elements and visual guidance (aligned with design system):
- A prominent header section with a large, editorial hero feel (serif display font for headings, sans-serif body) and ample white space.
- A filter bar containing:
  - Date range picker (from-to)
  - Text search field (invoice number, description, or plan)
  - Quick filter chips (All, Paid, Unpaid, Past Due, Refunded)
  - Export button (CSV/PDF) and per-record download actions
- A data table or card-grid of invoices/transactions with columns:
  - Date (formatted, sortable)
  - Invoice/Transaction ID
  - Description (e.g., "Subscription renewal", "One-time charge")
  - Plan/Product (if applicable)
  - Amount (currency-aware formatting)
  - Status (Paid, Unpaid, Past Due, Refunded, Canceled)
  - Download (PDF/CSV)
- Invoice detail modal/drawer:
  - Billing address, company name, contact, tax IDs if applicable
  - Line items (description, quantity, unit price, amount)
  - Subtotals, taxes, discounts, total
  - Payment method and last payment date
  - View raw payload / audit trail toggle if needed
- Pagination controls or infinite scrolling (prefer pagination for predictability)
- Subtle, accessible hover/focus states and keyboard support

Mandatory coding standards — runtime safety (non-negotiable):
- Supabase / API results: Always guard against null results
  - Example: const invoices = data ?? []
- Array operations: Guard against non-arrays or null/undefined
  - (invoices ?? []).map(...), or Array.isArray(invoices) ? invoices.map(...) : []
- useState defaults for arrays: initialize with proper type
  - const [invoices, setInvoices] = useState<Invoice[]>([])
- API response shapes: validate before usage
  - const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Optional chaining and defaults:
  - const firstInvoice = invoices?.[0]
  - const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
- Destructuring with defaults wherever API responses are consumed
  - const { data: invoiceList = [] } = apiResponse ?? {}

---

## Components to Build

1) TransactionHistoryPage
- Purpose: Orchestrates data fetching, filtering, and rendering of the list and detail modal.
- Props: None (page-level)
- State:
  - invoices: Invoice[]
  - isLoading: boolean
  - error: string | null
  - filter: { query: string; startDate: string | null; endDate: string | null; status: string[] }
  - pagination: { page: number; pageSize: number; total: number }
  - selectedInvoice: Invoice | null
  - showDetailModal: boolean
- Behavior:
  - Fetch invoices with applied filters and pagination
  - Guard all results using data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks
  - Open detail modal on row action
  - Trigger export of current view (CSV/PDF)

2) InvoiceListTable
- Purpose: Render a performant, accessible table of invoices
- Props:
  - invoices: Invoice[]
  - onView(invoice): void
  - onDownload(invoice, type): void
- UI:
  - Table with accessible header (th) and ARIA roles
  - Sortable Date column (client-side if server-side sort not available)
  - Row actions for PDF/CSV download
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable
  - Proper aria-labels and descriptive titles

3) InvoiceDetailModal
- Purpose: Display detailed invoice information
- Props:
  - invoice: Invoice
  - onClose(): void
- UI:
  - Billing address, company, items, taxes, totals
  - Copyable fields where appropriate
  - Close on Escape
- Data handling:
  - Safely render line items and totals with guards (e.g., (invoice.items ?? []).map(...))

4) ExportBar
- Purpose: Provide export options for current view
- Props:
  - invoices: Invoice[]
  - onExport(format): void
- UI:
  - Dropdown or segmented control for PDF/CSV
  - Accessible label and tooltip

5) FiltersBar
- Purpose: Date range, search, status chips
- Props:
  - filter: FilterState
  - onFilterChange(nextFilter): void
- UI:
  - Date range pickers (start, end)
  - Search input
  - Status chips with inclusive multi-select

6) BillingMetadataPanel (optional, in invoice detail or side panel)
- Purpose: Show added billing metadata on a per-invoice basis
- Props:
  - invoice: Invoice

7) API Helpers / Services
- invoiceService.ts
  - fetchInvoices(params): Promise<{ data: Invoice[]; total: number } | null>
  - downloadInvoice(invoiceId, format): Promise<Blob>
- billingService.ts
  - fetchBillingMetadata(invoiceId): Promise<BillingMetadata | null>

8) Data Models (TypeScript interfaces)
- Invoice
  - id: string
  - date: string (ISO)
  - description: string
  - planName?: string
  - amount: number
  - currency: string
  - status: 'paid' | 'unpaid' | 'past_due' | 'refunded' | 'canceled'
  - pdfUrl?: string
  - csvUrl?: string
  - items?: InvoiceItem[]
  - billingAddress?: Address
  - paymentMethod?: string
  - metadata?: any
- InvoiceItem
  - id: string
  - description: string
  - quantity: number
  - unitPrice: number
  - amount: number
- Address
  - line1: string
  - line2?: string
  - city?: string
  - state?: string
  - postalCode?: string
  - country?: string
- BillingMetadata
  - billingAccountId?: string
  - customerId?: string
  - entitlements?: string[]
- FilterState
  - query: string
  - startDate: string | null
  - endDate: string | null
  - status: string[]

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend

- Architecture:
  - Use a modular component architecture with clear separation of concerns.
  - Use React with TypeScript (or your preferred TS framework) and a state management approach suitable for the app (e.g., useState/useEffect, context, or lightweight store if present).
  - Ensure all components are accessible (ARIA roles, keyboard interactions).

- UI Components:
  - Responsive layout with a centered content column, max width 900–1000px for the hero/content area, and generous padding as per design language.
  - Cards for individual invoices or a table layout with proper cell padding, readable fonts, and hover/focus states.
  - Buttons: Primary green (#2f6f63), Secondary teal/gray-teal (#2b6250) with accessible contrast.
  - Modals/Drawers: Invoice detail modal with focus trap and escape-to-close behavior.

- Data Handling:
  - All data fetches should safely handle nulls: data ?? [], Array.isArray checks, and defaults for missing fields.
  - Dates should be displayed in a user-friendly format (e.g., MM/DD/YYYY or locale format) with consistent time zone handling.
  - Currency formatting must respect the invoice currency (e.g., USD, EUR) using Intl.NumberFormat.

- Interactions:
  - Date range filters must constrain inputs and debounce rapid changes to reduce re-fetching.
  - Search must debounce (e.g., 250ms) to avoid excessive requests.
  - Sorting (if implemented) should be stable and reflect in accessible text for screen readers.
  - Downloads must initiate a non-blocking fetch and trigger a blob download with correct file naming.

- Backend and API layer (assumed available endpoints; implement stubs where needed):
  - GET /invoices?startDate=&endDate=&query=&status=&page=&pageSize=
  - GET /invoices/:id (for detail)
  - GET /invoices/:id/download?format=pdf|csv
  - GET /billing/:invoiceId/metadata (optional; surface billing metadata)
  - Security: Ensure endpoints require proper authentication tokens or session cookies; handle 401/403 gracefully.

- Validation:
  - Validate responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Ensure numeric amounts are finite: Number.isFinite(amount)
  - Ensure required fields exist before rendering; gracefully degrade if missing (e.g., show "N/A" for missing plan or address).

- Performance:
  - Implement pagination or virtualization for large lists.
  - Use memoization where appropriate (e.g., computed status counts, filtered lists).

### Backend

- APIs/Endpoints:
  - Invoice retrieval with filtering and pagination
  - Invoice detail retrieval
  - Invoice download generation (PDF/CSV) with deterministic naming
  - Optional: billing metadata retrieval
- Database Tables (schemas; simplified):
  - invoices
    - id (PK)
    - date (timestamp)
    - description (text)
    - plan_name (text, nullable)
    - amount (numeric)
    - currency (text)
    - status (text) // paid, unpaid, past_due, refunded, canceled
    - pdf_url (text, nullable)
    - csv_url (text, nullable)
    - billing_address_id (FK)
    - payment_method (text, nullable)
  - invoice_items
    - id (PK)
    - invoice_id (FK)
    - description (text)
    - quantity (int)
    - unit_price (numeric)
    - amount (numeric)
  - addresses
    - id (PK)
    - line1, line2, city, state, postalCode, country
  - billing_metadata
    - invoice_id (FK)
    - billing_account_id (text)
    - customer_id (text)
    - entitlements (text array)

- Business Logic:
  - Enforce null-safety at the API level; ensure that missing fields return defaults in the response shape.
  - Ensure idempotent and retry-safe download endpoints; generate PDFs/CSVs with deterministic naming like invoice_{id}.pdf.
  - Apply rate-limiting on export endpoints to protect resources.

### Integration

- Data Flow:
  - Frontend calls fetchInvoices with filters; backend returns invoices array (and total count) with safe defaults.
  - User selects an invoice to view; frontend calls fetchInvoiceDetail or fetches embedded detail from the list if included.
  - User clicks download; frontend calls downloadInvoice with format; response triggers file download via blob link.
- State Sync:
  - When a user applies filters, the page resets to page 1 and fetches new data.
  - When an invoice detail is opened, ensure that related billing metadata is available; if not, fetch additional data.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) User lands on Order / Transaction History page
- See a hero/header area with a clean, premium fintech aesthetic.
- A FiltersBar at the top with date range, search, and status chips.
- A list/table of invoices with columns: Date, ID, Description, Plan, Amount, Currency, Status, Downloads.
- A prominent Export button in the filter area to export current view (CSV/PDF).

2) User applies date range or search
- Page shows a loading state (spinning indicator or skeleton rows).
- Invoices list updates to reflect filters, with correct null-safe rendering and price formatting.

3) User filters by status (Paid, Unpaid, Past Due, Refunded, Canceled)
- List updates to match selections; counts can be surfaced if needed.

4) User clicks an invoice row or actions
- InvoiceDetailModal opens, showing full details: billing address, line items, taxes, totals, and payment method.
- Option to close the modal with Escape or an on-screen close button.

5) User downloads an invoice
- Click PDF/CSV download for a specific invoice.
- Browser triggers file download; UI shows a brief success toast or non-blocking confirmation.

6) User uses Export
- Clicks Export for CSV or PDF; a file downloads for the current view range and filters.

7) Edge cases
- No invoices found: show empty state with guidance to adjust filters.
- Partial data: render available fields with fallbacks (e.g., description missing -> "No description").

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: (TypeScript interfaces)
  - Invoice, InvoiceItem, Address, BillingMetadata, FilterState
- API Endpoints (example):
  - GET /api/invoices?startDate=&endDate=&query=&status=&page=&pageSize=
  - GET /api/invoices/{id}
  - GET /api/invoices/{id}/download?format=pdf|csv
  - GET /api/invoices/{id}/billing-metadata
- Security:
  - JWT/token-based authentication; include Authorization header
  - Server-side authorization checks for access to invoices
  - Error handling for 401/403, with user-friendly messages
- Validation Rules:
  - Dates are ISO strings; validate format before sending
  - Ensure numeric fields (amount, unitPrice) are finite numbers
  - Validate that status is one of allowed values
- Data Handling Rules (Runtime Safety):
  - const invoices = data ?? []
  - const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Initialize arrays with useState<Type[]>([])
  - Optional chaining for nested fields (invoice?.billingAddress?.city)

---

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] The page renders a searchable, filterable list of invoices with correct date formatting, amount formatting, and status display.
- [ ] All data accesses guard against null/undefined: (data ?? []), Array.isArray checks, and proper useState([]) initialization.
- [ ] Invoice detail modal opens on request and shows complete information (billing address, line items, totals, payment method) with proper guards for missing fields.
- [ ] PDF/CSV downloads for individual invoices work reliably; downloads trigger with correct file naming and content-type.
- [ ] Export current view (CSV/PDF) works with applied filters and pagination; backend handles large exports without breaking the UI.
- [ ] Date range and search filters debounce appropriately; loading states appear during fetches.
- [ ] Security: API endpoints require authentication; 401/403s are handled gracefully in the UI with prompts to re-authenticate.
- [ ] UI adheres to the design system and visual style, including typography, color palette, spacing, and responsive behavior.

---

## UI/UX Guidelines

Apply the project's design system and visual style:
- Color Palette:
  - Primary Green: #2f6f63
  - Secondary Teal/Gray-Teal: #2b6250
  - Neutral White: #ffffff
  - Page Background Taupe: #a79e96
  - Hero Beige: #f3efe6
  - Text Dark: #1f1f1f
  - Body Text Gray: #555555
  - Card Shadow: rgba(0,0,0,0.08)
  - Accent Brown: #3b2b1e
  - Accent Orange: #e07a4c
- Typography:
  - Headings: serif display font (Playfair Display or Georgia)
  - Body: sans-serif (Inter or Roboto)
- Layout:
  - Wide hero with centered content; max content width 900–1000px for the hero
  - Generous left/right padding; rounded card surfaces; soft shadows
- Key Design Elements:
  - Cards: 16–20px radius, 0 6px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.08) shadow, hover lift
  - Navigation: white top bar, centered links, right-aligned actions; primary action button in green
  - Interactive Elements: rounded CTAs, forms with light borders, focus rings in green
- Data Visualization:
  - Not required; if added, use the same neutral palette with teal/green accents

